<DOC><DOCNO> AP880720-0103 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0837EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u p PM-CVN--MissingDynamite     07-20 0273</FIRST><SECOND>PM-CVN--Missing Dynamite,0281</SECOND><HEAD>Police Search For Stolen Dynamite</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal, state and city authorities searched thecity today for a van loaded with more than 100 pounds of stolendynamite after a telephone caller reportedly told police it wouldbe used to bomb an abortion clinic.   There was no indication the theft was related to the DemocraticNational Convention, said police spokeswoman Myrna May.   The tan van involved in the heist was reportedly sighted inseveral locations around the city, including the state Capitol andThe Omni, where the convention that brought 35,000 visitors to thecity was being held, Ms. May said.   Atlanta Police Sgt. G.E. Smith, assigned to the conventioncommand center, said no arrests had been made.   The dynamite was stolen early Tuesday from a suburban blastingcompany by a ski-masked bandit, officials said.   The Atlanta Constitution, quoting unidentified sources, saidpolice received a call saying the dynamite would be used against anabortion clinic. Police had been warned that an abortion clinicwould be blown up during the convention, the newspaper said.   Atlanta police and convention security officers were alerted tothe theft by the Henry County Sheriff's Department. Sheriff's Capt.Keith McBrayer said two cases, each containing 50 pounds ofdynamite, or about 200 sticks, and 200 blasting caps were taken.   The FBI, the Georgia Bureau of Investigation, the Secret Serviceand the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms have joinedpolice from Atlanta and Henry County in the search, officials said.   ``They've detected no connection with the convention,'' said GBIspokesman John Bankhead. ``But the convention security people arecertainly aware of this.''</TEXT></DOC>